what is the Moscow treaty on strategic offensive reductions? The Moscow treaty on strategic offensive reductions is a bilateral treaty signed in Moscow on 24 May 2002 by the presidents of the United States and Russia. The treaty aims to reduce the number of strategic nuclear weapons held by the two countries. The Moscow treaty is part of a series of arms control agreements between the United States and Russia. It is the successor to the START I treaty (1991) and the START II treaty (1993). The treaty was signed by President Bush and President Putin
